Administrators said they realized the problem before lunch was served and removed references to Black History Month from the menu, reports the Indianapolis Star.

School officials blamed the menu mistake on Aladdin Food Management Services, which puts together meals without Park Tudor approval.

A school official said the menu was ‘unconsciously’ linked to Black History Month by the West Virginia-based food services provider, without realizing any racist connotation.

Fried chicken became ‘one of the most egregious stereotypes’ about blacks, along with watermelon, to emerge from minstrel shows, said Jakobi Williams, an Indiana University history professor.

